{{1922 Big Ten football standings}}
The '''1922 Michigan Wolverines football team''' represented the [[University of Michigan]] in the [[1922 college football season]]. In [[Fielding H. Yost]]'s 22nd season as head coach, Michigan compiled a record of 6<U+2013>0<U+2013>1 (4<U+2013>0 in [[Big Ten Conference]] games), outscored opponents 183<U+2013>13, and tied with [[1922 Iowa Hawkeyes football team|Iowa]] for the Big Ten championship.  On defense, the team did not allow its opponents to score a point in the first five games of the season, and its scoring defense of 1.8 points per game is among the lowest in Michigan football history.

Highlights of the 1922 season included participation in dedication games for [[Vanderbilt University]]'s [[Vanderbilt Stadium|Dudley Field]], the first large athletic stadium in the South, and [[Ohio State University]]'s [[Ohio Stadium]].  At the dedication game for Ohio Stadium, the Wolverines shut out the Buckeyes, 19<U+2013>0.

Halfback [[Harry G. Kipke|Harry Kipke]] led the team in scoring with 48 points in six games, handled punting responsibilities, and was also one of the team's best defensive players.  Kipke was a consensus [[1922 College Football All-America Team|All-American]], receiving first-team honors from [[Walter Camp]], ''Athletic World'', [[Walter Eckersall]], [[Norman E. Brown]], and Lawrence Perry.  Team captain and right end [[Paul G. Goebel|Paul Goebel]] was also selected as a first-team All-American by ''Athletic World'' magazine based on polling of 250 coaches.  Left end [[Bernard Kirk]], who received first-team All-American honors from Eckersall, died of meningitis in December 1922 after sustaining a brain injury in an automobile crash.  

